Business Day

INVESTING WITH: Brian S. Posner; Warburg Pincus Growth and Income Fund

By ABBY SCHULTZAPRIL 19, 1998



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story









IF sheer assets were the benchmark for success in the fund business, then the move of Brian S. Posner to Warburg Pincus Asset Management would have been a humbling one.At Fidelity Investments, he built his reputation as a value investor at the Equity-Income II fund, which had $15.5 billion in assets when he left. By contrast, his new fund assignment, Warburg Pincus Growth and Income, had less than one-thirtieth of that amount, under $500 million, when he took over.Of course, Mr. Posner and other people at at Warburg Pincus don't measure success that way. They point to performance. Since he joined the firm as a partner and portfolio manager in January 1997, Mr. Posner has raised the performance of the Growth and Income fund, formerly a laggard, to the top quartile among its peers in the last 12 months. And its assets have grown to almost $1 billion.Mr. Posner's presence is being felt throughout Warburg Pincus, which manages $22 billion in retail and institutional assets, as he takes on increasing management responsibilities. He is now director of large-capitalization domestic stock research and head of the firm's global asset allocation committee.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

''He has reinvigorated people here with his commitment to excellence,'' said Arnold M. Reichman, chief operating officer of Warburg Pincus, a private firm that began selling its funds to the public only in 1992. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





Known for his personable nature, Mr. Posner has encouraged a less formal exchange of ideas among analysts. That, in turn, has helped Warburg Pincus portfolio managers gain insights into companies that otherwise may have remained only scribbles in an analyst's notebook.''I've always found the more you can get analysts to talk about companies, the more ideas that get generated,'' Mr. Posner said. The Warburg Pincus Balanced fund, which Mr. Posner plans to help run, will also draw on the large-cap domestic stock research, as funds like Strategic Value and Capital Appreciation already do.Mr. Posner, 36, said he had longed to play a bigger role in building a business. At Fidelity, he said, ''my opportunities did not go much beyond running a fund.''So how is Growth and Income performing under Mr. Posner? Since he took over, it has returned 34.5 percent, annualized, through April 10, according to Morningstar Inc., the financial publisher in Chicago. That beats the 30.7 percent return for the average large-capitalization value stock fund, though it lags behind the Standard & Poor's 500-stock index, at 38.5 percent.But if history is a guide, Mr. Posner's fund will close the gap with the S.& P. over time while taking on less risk. Fidelity Equity-Income II had an annualized total return of 17.1 percent during Mr. Posner's tenure, from April 1992 to December 1996, just shy of the 17.2 percent for the S.& P. But the fund's price-to-earnings and price-to-book ratios were typically far below those of the index, and Mr. Posner figures that the fund was only 75 percent as risky. And Equity-Income II easily beat its average peer fund, which returned just 15.6 percent, annualized, over that period. (Under Mr. Posner's successor, the veteran Fidelity manager Bettina Doulton, Equity-Income II has continued to do well, returning an annualized 32.1 percent though April 10.)Mr. Posner is running the Growth and Income fund much as he did Fidelity Equity-Income II. One difference, he said, is that he does not have to compete with other Fidelity managers when he buys a stock; if he likes something, he can buy as much as he wants. Another is that Growth and Income is smaller, so he can own fewer stocks. There are about 100 companies in Growth and Income; Equity-Income II had about 170, he said.The core of his approach is what Mr. Posner likes to call ''absolute valuation.'' It is a combination of fundamental, kick-the-tires, talk-to-management analysis and ''valuation analysis,'' which weighs earnings as well as present and future return and risk. A key measure is free cash, which in effect is earnings that can be reinvested or passed on to shareholders.
