''I want to make sure on an absolute basis, in isolation, I can make money on this company,'' Mr. Posner said.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Mr. Posner is nothing if not patient. He may pore over numbers for years before he takes the plunge on a stock. A favorite example is British Petroleum. The company was in dire straits during the early 1990's and announced a major restructuring in August 1992. Mr. Posner made a few trips to Britain to explore the situation and quickly began buying the American depositary receipts, then trading at about $22.''Shortly thereafter it became one of my largest positions,'' Mr. Posner said. The A.D.R.'s are now at $89.6875.He still likes B.P., which makes up 2.8 percent of Growth and Income's portfolio.  The company has announced a major share buyback and plans to increase production by 25 percent over the next five years; Mr. Posner thinks the stock may climb as high as $120 a share in the next 12 months.Another long-term favorite is Unova Inc., a $1 billion industrial technology company based in Beverly Hills, Calif., that was spun off last October by Western Atlas, an oil-services concern. Unova traded as low as  $14.1875 a share in January and is now at $22.375, or under 16 times 1999 per-share earnings estimates. Mr. Posner describes Unova as ''the proverbial eight-cylinder car running on four cylinders'' that will soon take off and could hit the high $20's in the near term.The company designs and builds manufacturing lines for engine makers, as well as bar-code systems for various commercial uses. Last year, the company's bar code business had to digest acquisitions, depressing operating margins.Mr. Posner, however, focused on the company's ability to generate free cash, which he expects to climb to $1.40 a share in 1999 from about $1.10 a share in 1998, and on its ability to eventually expand its businesses.Not all of Mr. Posner's stocks are holdovers from his Fidelity days. His new analysts have brought some new stocks to his attention, like Gulfstream Aerospace, the maker of private jets.Mr. Posner was convinced by his defense and aerospace analyst that the GV, Gulfstream's newest jet, would be introduced on time and on budget. Moreover, he estimated that Gulfstream's free cash could hit $3.25 to $3.50 a share in 1999, versus $2.25 a share in 1998. He bought the stock last spring when it was trading at about $24; it is now at $45.75.Mr. Posner also keeps his eye on the portfolio mix, balancing volatile and steady stocks to keep the fund's risk in check. But as stock prices have climbed, Mr. Posner has had more difficulty finding stocks he likes. He is looking into semiconductor equipment makers and disk drive manufacturers, though he is not convinced that any are worth buying yet.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

In general, Mr. Posner says this is a time to exercise caution in the market, and not to swing for the fences. ''In this environment, consistent with the diversification in the portfolio and risk management, it's about doubles and singles and moving the runners and not striking out,'' he said. Continue reading the main story






